=========================================
3. Container vs Iterator Type
=========================================

vector        -> Random Access
array         -> Random Access
deque         -> Random Access

list          -> Bidirectional

set           -> Bidirectional
multiset      -> Bidirectional

map           -> Bidirectional
multimap      -> Bidirectional

forward_list  -> Forward

unordered_set       -> Forward
unordered_multiset  -> Forward

unordered_map       -> Forward
unordered_multimap  -> Forward

=========================================
4. Why Does vector Have Random Access Iterator?
=========================================

vector stores data in contiguous memory.

Example:

10 20 30 40 50

Iterator can directly jump:

it + 3
it - 2
it[1]

Supported.

=========================================
5. Why Does set/map Have Bidirectional Iterator?
=========================================

Implemented using Red-Black Tree.

Data is not contiguous.

Supported:

++it
--it

Not Supported:

it + 1
it - 1
it[0]

Interview Answer:

set/map provide Bidirectional Iterators because
they are tree-based containers. Elements are
not stored contiguously, so random access is
not possible.

=========================================
6. Common Iterator Operations
=========================================

begin()
-------
First element.

end()
-----
One position after last element.

rbegin()
--------
Reverse begin.

rend()
------
Reverse end.

Example:

for(auto it = v.begin();
    it != v.end();
    ++it)
{
    cout << *it;
}

=========================================
7. Iterator vs Pointer
=========================================

Pointer:
--------
Works with arrays.

Iterator:
---------
Works with STL containers.

Iterator behaves like a generalized pointer.

=========================================
8. Iterator Invalidation (VERY IMPORTANT)
=========================================

vector
------
Insertion may invalidate iterators.

Example:

v.push_back(100);

May reallocate memory.

-----------------------------------------

set / map
---------
Insertion does NOT invalidate iterators.

Reason:

Tree nodes are linked.

-----------------------------------------

erase()
-------
Only iterator pointing to erased element
becomes invalid.

=========================================
9. Most Asked Interview Questions
=========================================

Q. What is an iterator?

A.
Iterator is an object used to traverse
elements of a container. It behaves
similar to a pointer.

-----------------------------------------

Q. Why are iterators needed?

A.
To provide a common traversal mechanism
for all STL containers and algorithms.

-----------------------------------------

Q. Which iterator does vector provide?

A.
Random Access Iterator.

-----------------------------------------

Q. Which iterator does set provide?

A.
Bidirectional Iterator.

-----------------------------------------

Q. Which iterator does map provide?

A.
Bidirectional Iterator.

-----------------------------------------

Q. Which iterator does unordered_map provide?

A.
Forward Iterator.

-----------------------------------------

Q. Why does vector provide Random Access Iterator?

A.
Because elements are stored in contiguous memory.

-----------------------------------------

Q. Why does set/map provide Bidirectional Iterator?

A.
Because they are implemented using
Red-Black Trees and do not support
direct indexing.

-----------------------------------------

Q. What is iterator invalidation?

A.
An iterator becomes invalid when a
container operation changes the element
it refers to or the underlying storage.

=========================================
ONE-LINE INTERVIEW ANSWER
=========================================

Iterator is an object similar to a pointer
that is used to traverse STL containers and
connect containers with STL algorithms.
